# Getting started — `{{ ip }}` verification environment

New to this environment (or to the team)? This is your entry point. It takes
you from a fresh checkout to your first passing simulation, then to your
first real task{% if has_copilot %}, then to working with the Copilot DV agents{% endif %}. The
full reference lives in [README.md](README.md).

## 0. Prerequisites

- **Cadence Xcelium** on PATH (`xrun`). The flow is Xcelium-only, single-step
  `xrun` with the bundled UVM-1.2. On most sites: log into a farm/interactive
  node and load the tool module first.
- **python3 + PyYAML** (the make flow parses configuration YAMLs with it).
{% if vips %}
- **`CDN_VIP_ROOT`** — this environment requests Cadence VIP
  ({% for v in vips %}{{ v.protocol|upper }} `{{ v.name }}`{% if not loop.last %}, {% endif %}{% endfor %}), so `make` refuses to run until
  `export CDN_VIP_ROOT=<your Cadence VIP install root>` is set. The VIPs
  themselves stay compile-clean placeholders until you enable them
  (`sim/vip_<protocol>.f`) — the variable just has to exist.
{% endif %}
{% if has_copilot %}
- Optional (for the agent workflow, step 5): VS Code with the GitHub Copilot
  extension, opened on this repo via Remote-SSH into the machine where `xrun`
  resolves — a local laptop window cannot simulate anything.
{% endif %}

## 1. First 15 minutes — prove the environment works

```bash
cd sim
make compile                       # 1) elaboration sanity - no test, stub DUT
make run TEST={{ ip }}_smoke_test        # 2) reset + traffic on every active agent
make matrix                        # 3) the run was recorded - see the summary
make waves TEST={{ ip }}_smoke_test      # 4) same run + waves.shm (SimVision)
```

Step 2 must end with `UVM_ERROR :    0` and `** UVM TEST PASSED **`, and
prints the configuration signature banner — every simulation self-identifies:

```
[UVM_GEN_CFG] config_name : {{ config_name }}
[UVM_GEN_CFG] param_hash  : {{ param_hash }}
{% for p in params %}
[UVM_GEN_CFG] param {{ p.name }} = {{ p.value }}
{% endfor %}
```

What just happened: the DUT is a generated **stub** (`tb/{{ dut_module }}_stub.sv`,
selected in `sim/dut.f`) and each agent drives a placeholder single-cycle
`valid` pulse protocol, so real transactions flow driver → monitor →
scoreboard/coverage before you have written anything. That is the point:
the plumbing is proven; only the protocol specifics are yours to fill.

Try the SoC-reuse switch too — same env, all agents passive, still green:

```bash
make run TEST={{ ip }}_smoke_test PASSIVE=1
```

## 2. Find your way around

| Where | What | State |
|---|---|---|
| `agents/<name>_agent/` | interface, item, driver, monitor, sequencer, cfg, agent, base seq | placeholder protocol, `// TODO` markers |
| `env/` | `{{ ip }}_env`, `{{ ip }}_env_cfg`, scoreboard, coverage, vsequencer, RAL, VIP wrappers | wired; compare logic = `PLACEHOLDER-CHECK` stubs |
| `seq_lib/`, `tests/` | virtual sequences, `{{ ip }}_base_test` / `{{ ip }}_smoke_test` | working |
| `tb/` | `tb_top.sv` + DUT stub | DUT ports unconnected (TODO) |
| `sim/` | Makefile, filelists, vsif, `scripts/cfg_tool.py` | working |
| `cfg/` | one YAML per configuration | `{{ input_basename }}` = this one |
| `verif_matrix.yaml` | append-only record of every run | live from your first `make run` |
{% if has_copilot %}
| `docs/`, `dv/`, `.github/` | agent-pack collateral (context, vplan, chkq, status) | see step 5 |
{% endif %}

## 3. Your first real tasks (in this order)

1. **Real protocol signals** — `agents/*/{{ ip }}_*_if.sv`, then the matching
   `*_driver.sv` (drive timing) and `*_monitor.sv` (observation). Grep `TODO`.
2. **Connect the DUT** — wire ports in `tb/tb_top.sv`, then flip `sim/dut.f`
   from the stub line to the real RTL filelist (pre-filled, commented).
   `make compile` after each step; on failures read the log named in the
   error, don't guess.
3. **Real checks** — `env/{{ ip }}_scoreboard.sv`: every `PLACEHOLDER-CHECK`
   stub becomes a real compare with a **stable check ID** (e.g.
   `SCBD_DATA_CMP`) reported via `uvm_error`.
4. **Real coverage** — `env/{{ ip }}_*_cov.sv`: replace the example bins; tag
   every bin `// VP-xxx` against `docs/vplan.md`{% if not has_copilot %} (create one){% endif %}.
5. **RAL** — swap `env/{{ ip }}_reg_block.sv` for your ralgen/IP-XACT model.
{% if vips %}
6. **Cadence VIP** — per protocol: uncomment `sim/vip_<protocol>.f` (define +
   VIP filelist) and fill the `` `ifdef `` TODOs in `env/{{ ip }}_<name>_vip.sv`.
{% endif %}

Multi-configuration work (`cfg/*.yaml`, `make run CFG=...`, `make regress`,
sign-off via `verif_matrix.yaml`) is covered in [README.md](README.md).
{% if has_copilot %}

## 4. Verify like the team does

The repo carries the team's verification methodology:

- `docs/CLAUDE.md` — per-IP context (pre-filled from this generation).
  **Keep it current**; both humans and agents read it first.
- `docs/vplan.md` — the traceability contract: every test/covergroup maps to
  a `VP-{{ IP }}-xxx` item. Draft it from the spec early.
- `docs/methodology/definition-of-done.md` — what "done" means for any item.
- `dv/tests/negative/` — the chkq checker-qualification kit (staged;
  activation checklist in `dv/lists/chkq.list`). Negative tests prove your
  checkers can actually catch bugs.
- `dv/cov/exclusion_requests.md`, `dv/lists/`, `dv/status/` — exclusion
  proposals, regression lists, session/cockpit records.

## 5. Working with the Copilot DV agents

{% if copilot_in_repo %}
This workspace carries the team's GitHub Copilot agent pack at the
repository root (`.github/`) — it serves every `*_verif` environment in it:
{% else %}
This environment ships the team's GitHub Copilot agent pack (`.github/`):
{% endif %}
seven specialized agents that write tests, stimulus and checkers, close
coverage, and triage failures — under hard no-shortcut rules (RTL read-only,
no checker weakening, no claim without a verdict).

Setup (once):

1. Open {% if copilot_in_repo %}the workspace root{% else %}this repo{% endif %} in VS Code **via Remote-SSH** on the machine where `xrun`
   runs; sign in to Copilot (agent mode) and `Developer: Reload Window` —
   the `dv-*` agents appear in the Chat view's agent picker.
2. Allow-list `make ` and `git diff`/`git log` in
   `chat.tools.terminal.autoApprove` (the golden-command mapping for this
   flow lives in `.github/copilot-instructions.md`).
3. Work in a git worktree per agent session.

Then type **`/start-here`** in Copilot chat — a guided, read-only onboarding
session: it tours this environment, runs the smoke test with you, inventories
the open `TODO`/`PLACEHOLDER-CHECK` work, and hands you ranked first tasks
with the right slash command for each. Day-to-day entry points:

| You want to... | Command |
|---|---|
| Guided first session (new engineer / new env) | `/start-here` |
| Know where you stand + what to do next | `/status` |
| Draft the vplan from the spec PDF | `/generate-vplan {{ ip }} <spec.pdf>` |
| Close a vplan item (test + covergroup) | `/close-vplan-item VP-{{ IP }}-xxx {{ ip }}` |
| Build reusable stimulus | `/build-stimulus <scenario> {{ ip }}` |
| Author real checks (from the PLACEHOLDER-CHECK stubs) | `/write-checkers <spec §> {{ ip }}` |
| Qualify checkers with negative tests | `/qualify-checkers <scope> {{ ip }}` |
| Debug a failing test | `/triage-failure <test> --seed N {{ ip }}` |
| Self-review before a MR | `/pre-mr-review` |

